comments.text: Park is absolutely not just bowls, it's anything inside a skatepark that's not a vert ramp. Many parks don't have a bowl, but it's still park skating. Street is strictly outside of skateparks, and technically anything built for the purpose of skating, even outside a skatepark proper like a home, is not considered street. You can alter street spots to make them skatable, ie bondo, brick rub, proping a sewer vent up with a board, taking off skate stoppers, and it's still street, it just can't be porpose built for skating. DIY is what you call something putpose built for skating outside of a proper park, but still isn't street. The X Games originally called park street until they changed it to park and now have real street on real skate spots. The X Games don't even have bowls in their park events(well I haven't watched them in a while but they never did for the many years I did) so saying park is a bowl is 100% wrong. It CAN have a bowl but that's only a small part of it. Flat rails and down rails, hubbas, euro gaps, pyramids, stairs, ledges, manny pads, outledges ect are all park obstacles and make up the majority of what is considered park, bowls are kinda niche in the scene and make up small portions of parks if they even have one.
